{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c2e0887c-8622-4c37-a8c8-95c3fbb50197","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, so I'll give you the configuration guidance directly.\n\nTo publish a C# MCP server as a **dotnet tool** on NuGet.org, add these properties to your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <RepositoryUrl>https://github.com/you/repo</RepositoryUrl>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\nKey requirements:\n\n1. **`PackAsTool` = true** — marks the project as a dotnet tool.\n2. **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command users will invoke.\n3. **`OutputType` = Exe** — tools must be executables.\n\nThen to pack and publish:\n\n```bash\ndotnet pack -c Release\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_NUGET_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\nUsers install it with:\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install --global MyMcpServer\n```\n\nAnd run it via `my-mcp-server` (which reads/writes stdio as expected for MCP).\n\nWould you like me to create or update the actual project file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"57a613df-308e-434a-a36a-d38a5118c867","outputTokens":448,"requestId":"C404:1E89:D15F3B:E5601A:69FBB4CB"},"id":"5ffc813a-555c-416f-a4ec-c17eb9087210","timestamp":"2026-05-06T21:38:28.959Z","parentId":"812b75c4-c589-4281-84bc-85a897d7a368"}
